{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778560599,"nonce":"Wbmx7fJyJwnoGslPH7GbfmUQNAc=","title":"Part of phase umbrella `f695729`. Follow-up from the `d448c9d` consultation synthesis (2026-05-11) — Tier 2 of the recommended path.","message":"The MVP (`410d7ac`) gave Δv = +78% for the trained linear regulator, while analytical Riccati on the same regime gives Δv = +1-27%. A 30× discrepancy means our training objective is **not** the Riccati game — we cannot interpret architectural comparisons (linear vs GRU) until we close this gap. This tier does two things at once: (a) builds a *true* trajectory tracker (non-trivial x_nom) for the structural proof of existence, and (b) calibrates the trained-linear pipeline against analytical Riccati.\n\n\n\nOne start, one target (no center-out direction generalization). Train four linear variants under **matched** plant/cost/horizon/adversary/delay:\n\n1. **LTV regulator**: `u_t = -K_t · (x_t - x_target)` — baseline\n2. **True LTV trajectory tracker**: `u_t = u_ff(t) - K_t · (x_t - x_nom(t))` where x_nom(t) is a learned (or teacher-initialized) time-varying nominal trajectory, u_ff(t) = inverse_dynamics(x_nom(t)) for a point mass with damping\n3. **K-frozen tracker**: only u_ff and x_nom trainable; K_t frozen to baseline regulator gain (Gemini Phase A)\n4. **u_ff-frozen tracker**: only K_t trainable; u_ff and x_nom frozen to teacher values\n\nAll warm-started: x_nom from minimum-jerk profile, u_ff from inverse dynamics, K_t from LQR or small stabilizing gains.\n\n**Decision criterion**: if (3) shows adversarial robustness with Δv ≈ 0 while (1) shows Δv \u003e 0, decoupling is mechanically possible for our plant under matched objective. If (2) under end-to-end training converges to (3)-like behavior, the optimizer can find decoupling on its own. If (2) collapses back to (1)-like Δv \u003e 0, the optimizer prefers the K-only basin and decoupling-via-parameterisation only works with strong inductive bias.\n\n\nGoal: make the trained LTV regulator (variant 1 above) reproduce the analytical Riccati Δv signature (+1-27% on rlrmp/C\u0026S regime). This requires aligning:\n\n- Plant (mass, damping, motor filter, sensory delay)\n- Horizon (timesteps + dt)\n- Q schedule (`(t/N)^k` exponent, normalisation)\n- R/control penalty\n- Disturbance channel (full-state `B_w` vs Frobenius-bounded `ΔA·x` — flavor-(a) vs flavor-(b) — see test_hinf_riccati.py xfail finding cross-ref'd from `c99ad9d`)\n- Delay treatment\n\n**Decision criterion**: if the trained linear regulator under the matched objective gives Δv in the +1-27% range, the pipeline is sound and architectural comparisons are meaningful going forward. If it still gives +78%, the training objective has additional couplings (regularizers, catch trials, hold losses) that need to be stripped before Tier 3.\n\n\nPer the codex consultation: do NOT report Δv alone. The primary diagnostic plot should be:\n\n- **x-axis**: nominal peak forward velocity (or movement time)\n- **y-axis**: a robustness metric — induced gain from disturbance to terminal/running error, OR worst-case adversarial loss under a strong held-out adversary, OR perturbation-rejection impulse response area\n\nDecoupling = \"for equal or better robustness, the adversarial model does not need higher nominal peak velocity.\"\n\n\n- Tier 1.1 (`0c95d6b`) ideally done first — its GRU affine decomposition results inform whether the decoupling framing survives empirically before we invest in architecture engineering.\n\n\n- Parent: `d448c9d` (decoupling acid test)\n- Umbrella: `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase)\n- Tier 1 sibling: `0c95d6b`\n- Consultation: `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/`\n- Related: `cea2e62` (analytical bridge to rlrmp cost), `9a0558e` (C\u0026S faithful Riccati, closed), `c99ad9d` flavor-of-`max` thread\n- Training-methods coord: `c99ad9d` (matched-objective is a training-method calibration)","files":null}]}